TY  - JOUR
TI  - Optimal pricing and recycling strategies in closed loop supply chain with promotional effort, cost-sharing contracts and subsidies under financing strategies
AU  - Verma, Poonam
AU  - Mishra, Vinod Kumar
T2  - INTERNATIONAL JOURNAL OF SYSTEMS SCIENCE-OPERATIONS & LOGISTICS
AB  - This paper explores financing strategies for a closed-loop supply chain (CLSC) led by collectors, focusing on the impact of capital constraints, government subsidies, and environmental activities. It examines the role of financing options like trade credit financing (TCF) and bank financing (BF) in enhancing CLSC sustainability and performance. We analysed a series of three-stage Stackelberg models that consider capital constraints, green activities, promotional efforts, and government subsidies for end-of-life (EOL) recycling. The models analyse equilibrium decisions and financing strategy selection, comparing TCF and BF across different operational scenarios. Results show that TCF benefits collectors by improving the recovery of interest income from EOL products. Government subsidies and cost savings from remanufacturing influence manufacturers' financing decisions, with TCF increasing CLSC profitability. A cost-sharing contract is identified as optimal for maximising profits. The study highlights the significance of government subsidies, reworking cost reductions, and growing environmental awareness for more effective financing decisions. Future research could investigate alternative financing models, such as equity or hybrid strategies, and their effects on CLSC performance. Additionally, further study is needed on the impact of dynamic market conditions, consumer behaviour, and regulatory changes on financing decisions in the context of collector-led CLSCs.
